COMP2011 Lab 4

Alien Invasion Game

In this lab, you'll have the exciting opportunity to dive into C++ one-dimensional arrays while building a simple "Alien Invasion" game. The lab will provide you with hands-on experience in managing an alien invasion using arrays.

Introduction

You are the commander of a space fleet defending Earth from an alien invasion. Your mission is to track the number of alien ships approaching Earth and engage them in battle. To do this effectively, you decide to implement a radar system using a one-dimensional array.

Mission Objectives
  1. Detect and Track Incoming Alien Ships: Each detected alien ship is represented by a positive non-zero integer ID. We allow duplicates of the same ID. You can track up to 5 alien ships at a time.
  2. Engage in Battle and Eliminate Alien Ships: Engage and eliminate alien ships as needed.
  3. Count Total Number of Alien Ships: Keep track of the total number of detected alien ships.
  4. Display Current Radar Status: Display the current radar status.
Additional Information
  • You don't need to worry about the IDs reaching the upper bound of C++ int type.
  • The maximum radar capacity is 5, meaning you can track up to 5 alien ships at a time.
  • Download this zip file containing skeleton code and test cases.
  • If your output file has extra whitespace in the last line, it will not affect the ZINC score.

Tasks

Radar System Implementation

You will be provided with a skeleton code that includes the main() function. Your task is to implement four functions to support the functionalities mentioned below:

  1. initialize_radar_system(int radar[]): Initializes the radar array.
  2. detect_alien_ship(int radar[], int alienID): Detects and tracks an incoming alien ship.
  3. engage_in_battle(int radar[], int alienID): Engages and eliminates alien ships with a specific ID from the radar. Returns the total count of eliminated alien ships.
  4. count_total_alien_ships(int radar[]): Counts the total number of detected alien ships.
  5. display_radar_status(int radar[]): Displays the current radar status.
Do's and Don'ts
  • You are not allowed to make any changes to the main() function.
  • You can only make changes to the function bodies of initialize_radar_system(), detect_alien_ship(), engage_in_battle(), count_total_alien_ships(), and display_radar_status().
  • You are not allowed to include any additional libraries beyond what is provided in the skeleton code.
  • Please do not modify any of the existing cout statements in the code in order to pass the provided test cases.
Radar Representation

The radar system in our game is maintained as a one-dimensional array, where each element in the array represents the presence or absence of an alien ship. For example:

Example 1

[1 1 1 0 0]

In this representation, [1 1 1] are the IDs of the detected alien ships, and the remaining spaces are empty.

Example 2

[31 22 69 9 0]

In this representation, [31 22 69 9] are the IDs of the detected alien ships, and the remaining spaces are empty.

Task 1: Initializes the radar array

Input: The radar array.(e.g., radar[MAX_RADAR_CAPACITY])

Return: No return value.

Objective: Initialize the input radar array. (Initialize all radar elements to 0 (no alien detected).)

Task 2: Detect alien ship

Input: The radar array, and the ID of the detected alien ship.

Return: Return true if the ship is successfully detected and added to the radar, return false if the radar is already full.

Objective: Try to detect and track the incoming alien ship. (If radar element is marked as 0, it means no alien ship is detected, so we can track alien ship.)

Task 3: Engage in battle

Input: The radar array, and the ID of the alien ship to be eliminated.

Return: Return the total count of eliminated alien ships.

Objective: Engage in battle and eliminate an alien ship from the radar.

Task 4: Count the total number of alien ships

Input: The radar array.

Return: Return the total number of detected alien ships.

Objective: Count the total number of alien ships currently in the radar.

Task 5: Display the current radar status

Input: The radar array.

Return: No return value.

Objective: Display the current radar status on the screen in the specified format. (e.g., Radar Status: [1 1 1 0 0])

Sample Input/Output

A sample input file:

4
0

A sample output file: (If your output file has extra whitespace in the last line, it will not affect the ZINC score.)

Alien Invasion Game Menu:
1. Detect and track an alien ship
2. Engage in battle and eliminate alien ships
3. Count total alien ships
4. Display radar status
0. Quit the game
Enter your choice: Radar Status: [0 0 0 0 0]
Enter your choice: Exiting the game. Goodbye!

Checking Before Submission

Please use the following methods to accurately check your program output against the sample output. It avoids simple mistakes (e.g., typo mistakes) that cause marks deduction in ZINC.

  • DO NOT use cerr because ZINC cannot grade cerr output. You can check this problem by following the checking procedures below.
  • DO NOT return a non-zero return code (e.g., return -1;) in the main function. ZINC will treat your program as "crash" and won't continue the grading.

Please compare your outputs with the desired outputs:

  • In VSCode, please open the terminal by one of the following two ways:
    • Press the key Ctrl+Shift+` in Windows/Linux, or Control+Shift+Backquote in Mac
    • From the menubar, select Terminal > New Terminal
    And then run this code to compile your code: 
    g++ -std=c++11 lab4.cpp -o lab4
  • You need to redirect the input of executable program to the txt test case files we provided, and redirect the output to different txt files. Here are the commands:
    • In MacOS or Linux: 
      ./lab4 < testcase/input1.txt > myOutput1.txt
    • In Windows: 
      Get-Content testcase/input1.txt | ./lab4 > myOutput1.txt

    Please replace the filenames accordingly if you would like to check other output files.

  • After that, you can compare your own output text files with the desired outputs one by one. You can compare any two files by VSCode:
    • Right click the first file you want to compare in VSCode Explorer, choose Select for Compare
    • Right click the second file you want to compare in VSCode Explorer, choose Compare with Selected

Grading Scheme

Each lab carries 3 points in total.

  • A student gets 1 point for attendance.
  • A student gets 1 point for a successful ZINC submission (lab4.cpp, the filename is case-sensitive)
    • The ZINC submission deadline is 10 minutes after your lab class. For example, if the lab end time is 12:50PM, the ZINC submission deadline is 01:00PM (i.e., 10 minutes after 12:50PM) on the same day.
  • A student gets 1 point for the Q&A session with the TA
    • The list of selected students will only be shown during the lab class.
    • If the student is not selected for the Q&A, then the ZINC submission will count for 2 points.
  • The filename is lab4.cpp, and submit it to ZINC. 50% penalty will be given if your filename is wrong.
  • You don't need to zip the file if you only submit one file to ZINC. Filename checking is enabled in ZINC. If your filename is wrong, you should see something like this:

If a student is unable to finish the lab and demonstrate to the TA by the end of the lab, they can only get the attendance point.
